summary:
The Security Council adopted Resolution 1336 (2001) on 23 January 2001, reaffirming previous resolutions on Angola, particularly 864 (1993), 1127 (1997), 1173 (1998), 1237 (1999), and 1295 (2000). 
The Council expressed concern over the humanitarian effects on the civilian population and determined that the situation in Angola constitutes a threat to international peace and security. 
Acting under Chapter VII of the UN Charter, the Council: 
- Took note of the final report of the monitoring mechanism (S/2000/1225); 
- Intended to consider the report; 
- Extended the monitoring mechanism's mandate for three months; 
- Requested periodic reports to the Committee and a written addendum by 19 April 2001; 
- Asked the Secretary-General to re-appoint experts and make necessary financial arrangements; 
- Requested the Committee Chairman to submit the addendum to the Council by 19 April 2001; 
- Called on States to cooperate with the monitoring mechanism; 
- Decided to remain seized of the matter.
